New Records: Australia posted the highest score of the T20 World Cup to date with 201/7.
Key Match Events: David Warner and Travis Head blitzed 70 runs in the first five overs.
Adam Zampa accounted for both of England's openers - Jos Buttler and Phil Salt - inside his first 11 balls.
Australia's total relied on cameos throughout their batting line-up with Warner top-scoring with 39.
England's middle order failed to adjust to a dry pitch quickly enough against a clinical Australian attack.
Marcus Stoinis, Tim David, and Matthew Wade ensured Australia reached 200 with regular boundaries at the back end.
Adam Zampa struck with his first ball, dismissing Phil Salt.
Jos Buttler reverse-swept Adam Zampa straight to Pat Cummins at point.
Post-Match Reflections: The result leaves England sweating on their qualification for the Super 8s.
England will almost certainly need to beat both Oman and Namibia to qualify for the second round.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The dimensions played a major role at Kensington Oval with one square boundary measured at just 58m.
For the first time in their T20 history, England opened the bowling with spin from both ends.
Australia's 74 for 2 was their highest powerplay at a men's T20 World Cup.
